The
Manchester
of
1750
was
a
place
so
different
from
the

Manchester
of
to-day,
that
if
any
inhabitants
of
the
old
place

could
revisit
their
old
home
they
would
imagine
themselves

to
be
in
fairyland.
There
has
been
a
new
earth,
if
not
a
new

heaven,
since
that
far-off
day.
The
streets
were
few,
narrow

and
tortuous.
Market
Street
was
a
quaint
old
alley.
Its

houses
of
overhanging
gables
were
so
close,
that,
when
a
broad

wheeled
waggon
was
dragging
along,
the
pedestrian
had
to

exercise
both
patience
and
ingenuity
to
avoid
destruction.
